{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491179"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"855"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/855"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.1,0.49,0.03,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"855"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103762"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/855"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"855"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86184"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"553"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44572"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103762"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents with a three month history of dull, persistent pelvic discomfort. He also mentions that the stream occasionally stops and starts while urinating, but that there is no pattern to when it occurs. He has a medical history significant for type 2 diabetes mellitus for 15 years. He takes three oral hypoglycemic agents with his most recent HbA1c level being 9.6%. Physical examination, including digital rectal examination is unremarkable. A plain abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the abnormality seen on the X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Faecolith","Phlebolith","Bladder stone","Lymph node calcification","Prostatic calcification"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe radiograph shows a smooth-surfaced, ovoid-shaped area of calcification within the pelvis which is most likely to represent a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebladder stone \u003C/strong\u003E(Image). These types of stones are largely asymptomatic, but may present with pain, infection and/or haematuria. In Western countries, the pathogenesis of bladder stones is complex but conditions that lead to urinary stasis is likely a contributing factor. In this patient, his poorly controlled T2DM put him at increased risk of developing neurogenic bladder, leading to the formation of a stone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhleboliths\u003C/strong\u003E typically appear with a radiolucent centre on plain radiograph. They are also much smaller than a bladder stone and are often incidental findings, rarely causing pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efaecolith of the appendix (appendicolith)\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen on plain radiograph but typically are seen within the right iliac fossa than centrally within the pelvis. They would also have associated localised tenderness in that region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E calcified lymph node\u003C/strong\u003E (LN) tends to have a more irregular surface to bladder stones, and appear with external calcification rather than internal or consistent rings of calcification. A history of granulomatous infection, lymphoma or autoimmune disease would support a finding of a calcified LN, which is absent in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstatic calcification\u003C/strong\u003E is increasingly associated with ageing. They are largely a normal, incidental finding on imaging of the prostate. If associated with benign prostatic hypertrophy, the calcium deposits remain largely asymptomatic, but may produce lower urinary tract symptoms if due to chronic prostatitis. There are often multiple, small stones \u2264 5mm in diameter, making this option unlikely to be the abnormality seen on this patient\u0027s X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bladder stones are often asymptomatic, being seen as a smooth-surfaced, ovoid-shaped area of calcification within the pelvis on plain X-ray."],"references":["Zulfiqar M, Shetty A, Tsai R, Gagnon MH, Balfe DM, Mellnick VM. Diagnostic approach to benign and malignant calcifications in the abdomen and pelvis. Radiographics 2020 Aug;40(3): 731-53. https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020190152","Childs MA, Mynderse LA, Rangel LJ, Wilson TM, Lingeman JE, Krambeck AE. Pathogenesis of bladder calculi in the presence of urinary stasis. J Urol. 2013 Apr;189(4):1347-51. Available from: doi: 10.1016/j.juro.2012.11.079","Tang Z, Wu XM, Wei Q, Wu LN. The prevalence and risk factors of prostatic calcification: an analysis of 68 705 subjects. Asian J Androl. 2018 Jul;20(4):417-19. Available from: doi: 10.4103/aja.aja_41_17"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86184"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"855"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20039"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20040"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20039"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/297557f7-617e-471d-b2d6-c4c8d00aad50.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/297557f7-617e-471d-b2d6-c4c8d00aad50.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":381,"height":480}},{"type":"media"